ot real provider/model quality.","test_description":"Configure a small budget, inject a stub API client, submit an over-budget document, and assert policy behavior (truncate or reject) occurs before send; verify whether client was called matches policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This requires a real AI provider call and real provider usage accounting. Mocked usage values can always be made compliant and hide real overruns from provider-side tokenization/accounting. Integration is disqualified by behavior text requiring \"provider-reported token usage,\" which a stub cannot validate.","test_description":"Execute live classification on representative documents with real provider usage metadata enabled; assert reported prompt+completion tokens are <= configured budget for each case, and fail on any over-budget call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.3,"Agentic":0.63,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is retry orchestration across modules: error mapping/backoff/retry loop -> caller result. In-process stubs can reproduce rate-limit responses and verify wait/retry control flow. Higher levels are disqualified because behavior checks transport-agnostic retry policy, not real model output quality.","test_description":"Use a stub API client that returns rate-limit on first call and success on second; run classify() with controlled clock/timer, assert at least one wait/backoff occurred, second 